\title{BVS.DAdj: Bayesian Variable Selection with Dual-Adjacency Network-Informed Ising Priors}
\description{
MCMC methods for Bayesian variable selection with Ising/MRF priors informed by graphical model adjacency. The bvs_mh sampler uses Metropolis-Hastings (MH) by default and also provides Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) and the No-U-Turn Sampler (NUTS) (Hoffman & Gelman 2014; Betancourt 2017) for active parameter-block updates in binary and time-to-event models; it supports binary logistic outcomes, continuous Gaussian outcomes, right-censored time-to-event outcomes via Cox partial likelihood, overdispersed count outcomes via a negative-binomial (Poisson-Gamma) representation, and imbalanced binary outcomes via cloglog or robust Student-t priors. The Polya-Gamma sampler targets binary logistic outcomes. Supports fixed, graphical lasso, and Bayesian GGM adjacency structures with dense and sparse high-dimensional variants under single and dual network priors. Allows additional covariates (z_dat) with coefficients (tau) that are always included in the model and not subject to variable selection.

MCMC tools for Bayesian variable selection with Ising/MRF
  priors. The \code{bvs_mh} sampler uses Metropolis-Hastings (MH) by
  default, with optional Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) and No-U-Turn
  Sampler (NUTS) active parameter-block updates for binary and
  time-to-event models; it supports binary logistic outcomes,
  continuous Gaussian outcomes, right-censored time-to-event outcomes
  via Cox partial likelihood, and overdispersed count outcomes via a
  negative-binomial (Poisson-Gamma) representation. The PG sampler
  targets binary logistic outcomes.
